The coordination driven self-assembled materials are in high demand of advanced energy chemistry, which remain largely unexplored. Here an ultra-simple and environmental friendly strategy for fabricating metal-organic gels (MOGs) in terms of electrochemical overall water splitting was reported. Through electrochemical testing, the Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG achieves the lowest oxygen evolution reaction (OER) overpotential of 285 mV (j10
   ), 347 mV (j100
   ), 445 mV (j500
   ) (GC electrode) and 173 mV (j10
   , NF electrode) in 1 M KOH, an ultra-low Tafel slope of 33 mV dec−1 and long-term stability, outperforming most of the reported polymer catalysts. On account of the moderate hydrogen evolution reaction (HER) performance (159 mV (j10
   )), thereby can drive the two-electrode electrolyzer at a relatively low cell voltage of 1.61 V (1.48 V when using Pt/C as cathode) and no significant attenuation after 20 h. Our work has demonstrated that the MOGs could break the shackles of current polymer catalysts for electrocatalysis.

ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
The coordination driven self-assembled materials are in high demand of advanced energy chemistry, which remain largely unexplored. Here an ultra-simple and environmental friendly strategy for fabricating metal-organic gels (MOGs) in terms of electrochemical overall water splitting was reported. Through electrochemical testing, the Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG achieves the lowest oxygen evolution reaction (OER) overpotential of 285 mV (j10
                     ), 347 mV (j100
                     ), 445 mV (j500
                     ) (GC electrode) and 173 mV (j10
                     , NF electrode) in 1 M KOH, an ultra-low Tafel slope of 33 mV dec−1 and long-term stability, outperforming most of the reported polymer catalysts. On account of the moderate hydrogen evolution reaction (HER) performance (159 mV (j10
                     )), thereby can drive the two-electrode electrolyzer at a relatively low cell voltage of 1.61 V (1.48 V when using Pt/C as cathode) and no significant attenuation after 20 h. Our work has demonstrated that the MOGs could break the shackles of current polymer catalysts for electrocatalysis.

ce:section.ce:para:
In addition to the catalytic activity, the electrochemical stability was also evaluated by conducting the chronoamperometry test. According to the result in Fig. 4f, the Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG displayed a long-term stability that no attenuation of current density was observed after 40,000 s OER testing under an overpotential of 285 mV (j10
                        ), while 16 % under 347 mV (j100
                        ) measured based on substrate Ni foam because of the effect of a large number of bubbles under high current. Here, we have speculated the reason for gradual decrease of current that the low adhesion of coating method would cause the material to fall off the Ni Foam, particularly when generating a lot of bubbles [46].

In light of the features of Ni-Fe bimetallic materials, the HER catalytic ability of proposed catalysts was further studied by drop-casting the prepared ink onto GC and Ni foam in 1 M KOH separately. When using Ni foam as the substrate, a low overpotential of 159 mV (j10
                        ) and 346 mV (j100
                        ) have achieved (Fig. 5
                        a). And the HER performance (with GCE) was depicted in Fig. 5b, the Ni-MOG has almost no activity. With the doping of iron, the HER performance has elevated until 40 %. It is a pity that the HER performance of Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG is somewhat not as good as commercial 20 % Pt/C catalyst. At the current density of 10 mA cm−2 and 100 mA cm−2, the Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG also exhibited the best HER activity and required overpotential of 387 and 464 mV, respectively (Fig. 5b). Whereas only 14 and 142 mV were needed for 20 % Pt/C. According to the Tafel equation, the Tafel slope values were fitted in Fig. 5c. The main sample exhibited the smallest Tafel slope of 63 mV dec-1 (73 mV dec-1 for Pt/C), implying the faster HER reaction kinetics. We have further investigated the durability through the chronoamperometry test, the current density (j10
                        ) showed little degradation (Fig. 5d), and the performance of Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG was pretty well (82 % maintained after 40,000 s).

The metal-containing coordination polymers tend to lack excellent electrical conductivity generally, which has in large part limited the development in electrocatalysis. In this work, we selected metal-organic gels (MOGs), a kind of hydrogels rarely used to be electrocatalyst, to overcome this shortcoming. In comparison to state-of-the-art noble RuO2, Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG exhibited a lower overpotential of 289 mV (j10
                     ), 343 mV (j100
                     ), and 445 mV (j500
                     ) using GC electrode, which is much lower when using the Ni foam electrode (only 173 mV at the current density of 10 mA cm−2). As for HER and overall water splitting, the performance of Ni0.6Fe0.4-MOG was also pretty well. The two-electrode electrolyzer assembled by this catalyst for water-splitting could offer a low cell voltage of 1.61 V to achieved j10
                      and maintained 90 % current density over 20 h stability test. The current study has verified the fact that the synthetic strategy was ultra-facile and inexpensive. And this material, owing to the outstanding conductivity, activity, and stability, to some extent, could be a promising candidate for highly conductive electrocatalytic materials.
